 title: 'Intellectual Property Theft & Contractor Fraud',
 subtitle: 'Systematic theft of creative work and refusal to pay for labor',
 severity: 'high',
 category: 'Commercial Crimes',
 date: 'December 5, 2013',
 lastUpdated: 'May 3, 2024',
 summary: 'Donald Trump and his businesses have a decades-long pattern of intellectual property theft and refusal to pay for work: using copyrighted music without permission, stiffing contractors, copying designs, and claiming credit for others\' work. This pattern of theft is documented across hundreds of lawsuits and represents systematic fraud.',
 content: [
 'MUSIC COPYRIGHT THEFT: Trump campaigns repeatedly used copyrighted music without permission or payment. Artists including Neil Young, Rihanna, Queen, Pharrell Williams, R.E.M., Adele, The Rolling Stones, and dozens more sent cease-and-desist letters that were often ignored. Trump\'s use of "Fortunate Son"(an anti-war song) at rallies particularly outraged its creator.',
 'CONTRACTOR NON-PAYMENT PATTERN: USA Today documented over 3,500 lawsuits involving Trump and his businesses, with hundreds alleging non-payment for completed work. Contractors, architects, carpenters, painters, plumbers, and suppliers across Trump projects describe the same pattern: work completed, payment demanded, settlement offered at fraction of value.',
 'SPECIFIC CONTRACTOR VICTIMS: Edward Friel Jr.\'s family cabinet-making business was driven to bankruptcy after Trump refused to pay for work on Harrah\'s casino. The Friels did the work; Trump paid 30 cents on the dollar. Hundreds of similar stories span decades of Trump projects.',
 'ARCHITECTURAL THEFT: Multiple architects have alleged Trump used their designs without proper payment. The pattern matches contractor fraud: commission the work, use the designs, then dispute the bill or refuse to pay.',
 'CASINO BONDS: Trump casinos issued junk bonds to fund construction, then defaulted, leaving bondholders and contractors unpaid while Trump extracted management fees. The pattern extracted value while leaving others holding the bag.',
 'TRUMP UNIVERSITY: Students paid up to $35,000 for "Trump\'s secrets "from "hand-picked "instructors who had never met Trump. The curriculum was generic. The "university "wasn\'t accredited. $25 million settlement for fraud reflected the theft of students\' money.',
 'GHOSTWRITER CREDIT: Tony Schwartz wrote "The Art of the Deal "but Trump claimed credit. Schwartz later expressed regret, saying the book created a false mythology and he shouldn\'t have put Trump\'s name on work Schwartz produced.',
 'BRANDING FRAUD: Trump licensed his name to developments he didn\'t own, letting buyers believe they were purchasing Trump properties. When developments failed, Trump disclaimed responsibility while having extracted licensing fees.',
 'CAMPAIGN MISREPRESENTATIONS: Trump claimed accomplishments, degrees, and experiences he didn\'t have. This pattern of claiming others\' work or fabricating credentials represents a form of intellectual theft.',
 'PATTERN EVIDENCE: The consistent pattern across decades and hundreds of victims isn\'t coincidence, it\'s business model. Extract maximum value, minimize payment, use legal resources to outlast opposition, settle when necessary for pennies on the dollar.',
 ],
